\begin_layout Standard
Some summary report of various different datasets holding word-pairs.
 All of the word-pair-counts were obtained by using the LG 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ANY
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 parser, which generates random planar graphs (random planar parse trees).
 Many of these datasets refer to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

MST
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and that is because those datasets 
\emph on
also
\emph default
 contain disjuncts (Sections) from MST parses.
 This additional data has no effect on the word-pairs; it just makes the
 datasets fatter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The common procedure used during this era was to take a tranche of text,
 perform random planar-graph parsing, and count the resulting word-pairs.
 Next, marginal statistics and word-pair MI is computed.
 Then the same tranche of text was run through the MST parser, and so disjunct
 stats are added.
 Then the next, and the next tranche are processed (up to a total of five
 distinct tranches, described below.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There were several problems encountered:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Early datasets include as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

words
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 character sequences that contain infix punctuation, typically because the
 input text used hyphens, dashes, double-dashes and commas to delimit words,
 but did not put spaces before or after the punctuation.
 The tokenizer was to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stupid
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to recognize these, and treated them as single words.
 Some of the datasets filter these out, after-the-fact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Same as above, with with sentence-ending periods.
 These can be recognized as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

words
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that have an embedded period, followed by a capital letter.
 None of the datasets have these filtered out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The MST parser was (mildly) buggy; when a sentence contained multiple instances
 of the same word, the generated disjuncts were incorrect.
 See bug
\emph on
 
\family typewriter
\emph default
opencog/atomspace#2252
\family default
 for the fix.
 This does not affect word-pair data, but does produce low-quality disjuncts
 that contribute to the overall noise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The inclusion of the MST data makes the datasets large and slow to load.
\end_layout

