\end_inset

 Note that this is quantitatively (and not just qualitatively) similar to
 the Chinese hanzi pairs distribution, shown below.
 Both have the same shape, and the slopes are only a little bit different,
 and the peak is slightly shifted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that a normal distribution takes the form of a parabola, when graphed
 on semi-log plot such as this.
 The parabola, here labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gauss
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, is given by the normal distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P=0.11\exp-0.1\left(MI-1\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

eyeballed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fit (it looks good, by eye), and not a precision numerical fit.
 As noted in an earlier experiment
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vepstas2009"

\end_inset

, a Gaussian distribution is symptomatic of randomly generated word-pairs:
 the low-MI word-pairs are effectively just noise, the completely random
 arrangement of nearby words.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

meaningful
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distribution - the excess of pairs with large positive MI are due to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true collocations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The RMS variation is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1=1/2\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

; solving, one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\sqrt{5}\approx2.2$
\end_inset

.
 The entropy of a normal distribution is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $H=0.5\log_{2}\left(2\pi e\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging in, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $H\approx3.2$
\end_inset

bits for the zero-mode distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Interpretation of the zero-mode
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gaussian in the above figure is slightly offset to the right, centered
 on an MI=1 rather than MI=0.
 As noted in
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vepstas2009"

\end_inset

, such an offset to positive MI is characteristic of an 
\emph on
incomplete
\emph default
 sampling of random text.
 That is, if one had a vocabulary of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 words, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{2}$
\end_inset

 possible word-pairs, each of which one might expect to see equally often,
 in the long-run.
 However, if one samples randomly generated sentences, and these sentences
 contain less than about 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{2}$
\end_inset

 words amongst all of them, then some pairs will never be observed.
 The resulting MI distribution will be a Gaussian, but it will be centered
 on a positive value of MI.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This should be compared to the distribution given below, for hanzi pairs.
 The effective hanzi vocabulary is much much smaller; about 
\begin_inset Formula $N=$
\end_inset

7K, as noted for 
\noun on
zh_pairs_sone
\noun default
.
 This vocabulary size allows for 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{2}=$
\end_inset

50M word-pairs to be observed, in principle, if they were randomly arranged;
 in practice 6M were observed.
 This is a much 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

deeper
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sample of all possible word-pairs than the English corpora allow; the English
 vocabulary is orders of magnitude larger.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experiments with randomly-generated corpora, given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vepstas2009"

\end_inset

 are interesting, but incomplete.
 They leave open multiple questions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How does the MI distribution change when random planar tree parses are used
 to obtain word-pairs, as opposed to clique-counting?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How does the MI distribution change as a function of sample size (holding
 the vocabulary size fixed)?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How does the MI distribution change as frequency of vocabulary words is
 altered from a uniform distribution to a Zipfian distribution?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last question is perhaps the most relevant: it implies that there is
 no finite-sized vocabulary; that all vocabularies are infinite.
 This is exactly what is seen, as more and more text is analyzed.
 A survey of the words in the 
\emph on
en_cfive
\emph default
 dataset shows more than a few (ancient) Greek words, written in the Greek
 alphabet.
 These are clearly 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

not English
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but they did appear in some English text, somewhere in the collection
 of corpora.
 They are rare; they necessarily can participate in only a small number
 of word-pairs.
 Yet most of the words in the dataset are like this - if not Greek, then
 Latin or Spanish or German (I guess there are travelogues amongst the corpora),
 and plenty of given names, surnames, geographical place names and the like.
 Each is increasingly more rare than the last, but the grand-total bulk
 of them is quite large.
 How does this large bulk of infrequent, unlikely word-pairs affect the
 MI distribution? How does it manifest itself?
\end_layout

