\begin_layout Section*
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above analysis has lead to several insights and proposals:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The distribution of word-pairs observed in natural language corpora have
 a clear bimodal distribution.
 One mode, termed the zero-mode, appears to consist of effectively random
 word-pairs, having little correlation or affinity to one-another.
 This mode reveals itself in several ways: the word pairs have a low MI
 value, and they are paired with a large variety of other words.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The zero-mode accounts for the majority of word-pair observations.
 However, it seems that it can be identified fairly cleanly, and thus removed
 or cut away.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The other mode consists of what might be termed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true collocations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true mode
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Based on this observation, it is relatively straight-forward to pose a hypothesi
s: if MST parsing is limited to pairs that are in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true mode
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, will this lead to higher-quality disjuncts and higher-quality grammars?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Maximal Planar Graph parsing strategy seems to offer a CPU-efficient
 mechanism for exploring the effect of different data cuts on disjunct quality,
 and should probably adopted as the primary pipeline parser.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The relationship between these two modes, natural language, and randomly-generat
ed pseudo-language remains a bit murky, despite an earlier investigation.
 In particular, the earlier experiments did not emulate the Zipfian distribution
 of natural language, and did not make any clear conclusions relating corpus
 size to vocabulary size.
 This omissions mean that it remains unclear which statistical properties
 are particular to natural language, and which statistical properties are
 typical of any random text.
 Understanding the differences between random corpora and natural text remains
 an important, unfinished task.
\end_layout

